# Backends must stay model-agnostic

Every backend under `backends/*/src/` is a **generic adapter**. It must support
multiple inputs and multiple outputs of generic datatypes via the
`TensorElement` variant and the `RawOutputTensor` path. It must NOT contain any
single model's tensor names, output count, or shape contract.

This mirrors Triton: the backend reports whatever the model file exposes; the
serving/config layer owns the named contract.

## Never do this

- Hardcode tensor names for a specific model:
  ```cpp
  // WRONG — bakes EdgeCrafter's contract into a generic backend
  std::string ecdet_input_name(size_t i) { return i == 0 ? "images" : "orig_target_sizes"; }
  ```
- Branch backend behavior on a model-shape heuristic:
  ```cpp
  // WRONG — every 2-in/3-out model is now mislabeled
  const bool ecdet_contract = meta->num_inputs() == 2 && meta->num_outputs() == 3;
  ```

This exact pattern was a real regression (commit `3a30266`, ExecuTorch). The
agent hit a genuine obstacle — the `.pte` format carries no tensor names — and
faked the names in the backend instead of solving it at the right layer.

## Do this instead

- Report what the model exposes. When the format carries names (ONNX, TensorRT,
  OpenVINO IR), read them (`getIOTensorName`, `GetInputNameAllocated`,
  `get_any_name`). When it does not (ExecuTorch `.pte`), emit positional
  `input_i` / `output_i` and let the serving runtime supply names from
  `config.pbtxt` (Triton-style overlay in `neuriplo-kserve-runtime`).
- Preserve generic multi-input / multi-dtype handling; do not narrow a backend
  to one input or one dtype.

## Reviewer / agent check before committing a backend "fix"

```bash
grep -rniE '"(images|orig_target_sizes|labels|boxes|scores|input_ids|pixel_values)"|num_inputs\(\)\s*==|num_outputs\(\)\s*==' backends/
```
Any hit in a generic backend is a model-specific leak — move it to config.
